{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1dd80b3-f319-4a86-88ff-7b4de2903cd6","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and how to fix it:\n\n---\n\n**1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter ref-safety scoping**\n\nC# 15 closes a ref-safety hole: `items` is backed by stack memory scoped to the loop body, so assigning it to `results` (which lives *outside* the loop) creates a dangling reference. The `scoped` modifier prevents escaping the method but doesn't prevent this narrower→wider scope assignment that C# 14 missed.\n\n**Fix:** Pre-allocate a span with sufficient lifetime:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    Span<int> results = stackalloc int[source.Length];\n    for (int i = 0; i < source.Length; i++)\n        results[i] = source[i] * 2;\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `Metadata.cs` — `nameof(this.Endpoint)` disallowed in attributes**\n\nC# 14 extended `nameof` to reach instance members in attribute contexts, but `this` has no meaning at attribute-evaluation time (there's no instance). C# 15 now rejects the explicit `this.` qualifier in that context.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the `this.` — the unqualified name is sufficient:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` contextual keyword ambiguity in collection expressions**\n\nC# 15 expanded collection expression parsing, and `with` is a contextual keyword (record `with { }` expressions). Inside `[with(x, y), z]`, the parser now tries to interpret `with(...)` as the start of a `with`-expression rather than a method call.\n\n**Fix:** Use the verbatim identifier `@with` to force it to be read as an identifier:\n\n```csharp\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\n\nOr rename the method to avoid the keyword clash entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17ab7ca7-8469-4235-83ed-a5352dc3e3e6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 15 / .NET 11 breaking changes. Let 